The paper deals with algorithmic problems related to strings and probability distributions, which are typically studied in the areas of data structures (cs.DS), computational complexity (cs.CC), discrete mathematics (cs.DM), computational geometry (cs.CG), and machine learning (cs.LG). The focus on the complexity of the Weighted Shortest Common Supersequence (WSCS) problem suggests cs.CC and cs.DM as likely categories, while the use of geometric techniques and the connection to the Weighted Longest Common Subsequence (WLCS) problem point to cs.CG and cs.LG as possible categories. The fact that the paper presents an algorithm with a tight upper bound also supports cs.DS as a likely category.
